begin_memory_text: At the beginning of the conversation, my partner asked me how my day went, I told her, and then we had exchanged names and talked about where we were from.
middle_memory_text: In the middle, we spoke about work, school, and a bit about the surveys that we took and why. We also spoke about our previous Betterup conversations and she said she met someone that was big into the deaf community.
end_memory_text: In the end, we spoke about her going to law school, and I told her my sister went to law school, she asked about Chicago's weather, she may be considering going to school there...we also talked a bit about prison reform.
rest_of_day_open: My plan is to come up with a strategy to envision myself out of my current situation. So I will chart, write out graphs and come up with a plan, possibly with family. I also plan to finish a book that I have been reading for the last couple of months.
critical_positive: I really like that my conversational partner did not let any silence fall in between, she had several questions to ask, which made it easier for me to answer instead of trying to think about what to say. I also enjoyed that we had common interests and were able to chat about that.
critical_negative: There is not much to say that went wrong in the conversation, I think it was evenly spaced out and we took turns chatting, there was not too much self-disclosure, just the right amount, if I could change anything thing I would slow the pace a tad and transition better between topics.

begin_memory_text: Who we are, where we're living, what we do for work, why we ended up where we are (she got into a car crash)
middle_memory_text: Prolific surveys, how we make money (she's an erotic novelist) weird experiences we've had, what it's like where we are
end_memory_text: Talked about what kind of law I want to do, her sister's a lawyer, human rights, prison reform
rest_of_day_open: I think it'll go well. I have pickleball tonight and a few meetings tomorrow, and I think I'll hear back from a law school I applied to within the next few days. I'm excited to see what happens over the weekend, and I'm going to go get ice cream to celebrate my law school acceptances from this week.
critical_positive: Chris seemed comfortable to talk to, and was willing to discuss basically whatever. I was able to take a step back and listen at times, and we bonded somewhat over shared experiences (taking surveys). I listened to her and validated her and what she does, which made things go smoothly.
critical_negative: She wasn't as energetic as other people I've spoken to, which made it a little harder to have a fun conversation. We also didn't have much shared life experience, which made discussions a little more boring. I tried to keep the energy up, which worked. She asked questions, which was helpful.
